        "canonical_link": "https://english.elpais.com/usa/2021-10-23/intimate-tales-from-the-closet-of-gabriel-garcia-marquez.html",
        "text": "‚ÄúLooking through someone‚Äôs closet is such an intimate thing,‚Äù says the actress Emilia Garc√≠a Elizondo, granddaughter of Nobel Prize-winning author Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez and his wife, Mercedes Barcha. Speaking from the inner courtyard of the house where Los Gabos, as the couple were known, lived for decades in the residential area of Jardines del Pedregal in Mexico City, Garc√≠a Elizondo explains that she has just spent two and a half months dusting, exploring and itemizing her grandparents‚Äô clothing.\n\nOn display are over 400 items that she has put up for sale: coats, dresses, bags, shoes, ties and handkerchiefs belonging to her grandparents. ‚ÄúLos Gabos left a lot of clothes, and we didn‚Äôt know what to do with it all,‚Äù she admits.\n\nThe house was left without both its long-term residents last year, following the death of Mercedes Bacha in August ‚Äì Garc√≠a M√°rquez passed away in 2014 ‚Äì and since then the family has been working to turn it into a cultural space. It will not be a museum, but a place dedicated to art which they have called the Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez House of Literature.\n\nThe first public event to let people see the famous home of Garc√≠a M√°rquez and Bacha is this clothing sale. In order to attend, it is necessary to make a prior appointment through the space‚Äôs Instagram account. But on the morning of October 20, close friends of the couple were invited to a preview to sift through the contents of Los Gabos‚Äô closet.\n\nGarc√≠a Elizondo explains that she selected items that were in good condition for the sale, or those that could be considered iconic. ‚ÄúWhat I most remember about Gabo [Garc√≠a M√°rquez] are his tweed jackets,‚Äù she says. There are around 20 of these emblematic coats that the Colombian author would wear on cold Bogot√° mornings or rainy Mexico City afternoons. One of the most valuable items, a black-and-white striped jacket, still carries a stain on an interior pocket from the time when one of his pens leaked. ‚ÄúWe also found a pen he used to sign his books in another jacket,‚Äù says Garc√≠a Elizondo, holding up a Sharpie that once belonged to the writer.\n\nThere are Calvin Klein, Armani and Hugo Boss items among Garc√≠a M√°rquez‚Äôs clothes, but what he always preferred were tailored clothes. ‚ÄúA lot of what was in his closet were things he had had made specifically for him. He ordered shirts with big pockets for his glasses and his pens,‚Äù Garc√≠a Elizondo says. In his vast library there is a table where some of these shirts are laid out with the names of his favorite tailors. ‚ÄúRa√∫l Gonz√°lez: shirt-maker,‚Äù features on many.\n\n‚ÄúHe also had a tailor called Jos√© Mej√≠a, who we think is Colombian. He had shirts made in France, Colombia and Italy.‚Äù Garc√≠a Elizondo decided not to add a tailored coat made for her grandfather by Emilio Velarde Rodr√≠guez in which the Nobel laureate signed his name in blue ink on a woven patch with the date of its acquisition, March 30, 1983. ‚ÄúI couldn‚Äôt part with that,‚Äù she says.\n\nGarc√≠a M√°rquez wasn‚Äôt a fashion icon, but neither did he underappreciate it. When it was announced in 1982 that he had won the Nobel Prize, one of the first things he said was that he hoped to attend the ceremony in emblematic Colombian attire. ‚ÄúI want to wear a guayabera,‚Äù he said at the time. ‚ÄúA tuxedo is the obligatory suit, but they allow Hindus to wear their national dress. I am willing to show that the guayabera is the national dress of the Caribbean and that I have the right to attend wearing one. As long as I don‚Äôt have to wear tails I can cope with the cold.‚Äù In the end he wore a Liqui liqui, the traditional suit of Los Llanos, the grassland plains that unite Colombia and Venezuela, in homage to his grandfather, a colonel who raised the young Garc√≠a M√°rquez and was closer to the writer than his own father. ‚ÄúHis wartime Liqui liquis and his civilian colonel‚Äôs whites looked as though he was still living inside them,‚Äù Garc√≠a M√°rquez wrote of his grandfather‚Äôs clothes in his memoir Living to Tell the Tale.\n\nThe famous white linen suit he wore in 1982 is not on sale in Mexico City: it is a well-guarded jewel in the National Museum of Colombia. Neither are his famous ruanas ‚Äì a poncho-style garment ‚Äì which remain at his home there. But the display in Mexico City does include what his wife wore to the Nobel ceremony, a floor-length emerald green dress with black leaves of thick fabric. It is not for sale though: it forms part of an exhibition alongside dozens more dresses that Barcha kept for decades.\n\n‚ÄúIt‚Äôs possible to trace all of the eras that Mercedes lived through,‚Äù says her granddaughter about the dresses and the tonal changes she saw in them. ‚ÄúThey run from her most colorful dresses to her most sober jackets toward the end [of her life].‚Äù On display are dozens of long indigenous dresses Barcha collected in various parts of Mexico, as well as several traditional bags made by the Wayuu people of Colombia. By contrast, there are Louis Vuitton bags and dresses made by Italian fashion house Marina Rinaldi. ‚ÄúI think Mercedes was completely obsessed with Marina Rinaldi,‚Äù says Garc√≠a Elizondo.\n\nThe proceeds from the sale of Barcha‚Äôs dresses and Garc√≠a M√°rquez‚Äôs tweed jackets are not destined for the Gabriel Garc√≠a M√°rquez House of Literature but for the FISANIM Foundation, run by Mexican actress Ofelia Medina to tackle malnutrition among indigenous children in states such as Chiapas and Guerrero. ‚ÄúI was 17 when I first met Gabo,‚Äù Medina tells EL PA√çS at the private viewing. ‚ÄúHe wrote the first draft plot of my first film, Patsy, Mi amor, sometime around 1967. At about the same time he finished One Hundred Years of Solitude. I was one of the first people who read that novel.‚Äù Medina remains close to the family and recalls when Garc√≠a Elizondo told her earlier this year about the donation that would be coming for her charity. ‚ÄúFor me it was as if yellow butterflies were fluttering all around me,‚Äù she says.\n\nThere are not many yellow butterflies in the Garc√≠a M√°rquez closet, but those stains in the Nobel winner‚Äôs pockets remain, from the pens which he used half a century ago to draw them."
